    text: `Cardio-respiratory endurance reflects the ability of the body’s circulatory and respiratory systems to supply fuel during sustained physical activity. To improve cardio-respiratory endurance, engage in activities that keep your heart rate elevated at a safe level for a sustained period, such as jogging, cycling, or swimming. Muscular strength is the amount of force a muscle or muscle group can exert in a single maximal effort (contraction). To increase muscle strength, work muscles against resistance, such as through weightlifting (under proper supervision) or bodyweight exercises. Muscular endurance is the ability of a muscle or muscle group to exert force against a submaximal load for an extended time or number of repetitions before fatiguing to the point of failure. Exercises like push-ups or planks can enhance muscular endurance. Body composition refers to the proportion of lean body mass to body fat, encompassing muscle, fat, bone, and other vital body components. Monitoring body composition is crucial for maintaining health and managing body fat levels. Flexibility is the range of motion available around a joint. Good flexibility can help prevent injuries throughout life, and activities like yoga, gymnastics, or a basic stretching program can improve it. Agility is the ability to change and control the body’s direction and position while maintaining constant, rapid motion, as seen in sports like soccer or basketball. Balance is the ability to control or stabilize the body, whether standing still or moving, such as when walking on a balance beam. Coordination is the ability to integrate the senses with body parts during movement, as in activities like catching a ball. Speed is the ability to move the body or its parts quickly, a critical factor in many sports to gain an advantage over opponents. Power is the ability to move body parts swiftly while applying maximum muscular force, combining speed and strength, as seen in actions like jumping or throwing.`
