    id: 91,
    title: "Typing Mitra DSSSB 91",
    difficulty: "Hard",
    text: `The images streaming out of Damascus this week will lodge in the memory for decades: jubilant crowds toppling the statue of Hafez al-Assad in Umayyad Square, young men weeping as they kissed the ground of their liberated capital, and the burned-out shell of the presidential palace still smouldering under a winter sky. After fifty-four years the Assad family's suffocating dynasty is finished. Bashar al-Assad - the mild-mannered ophthalmologist turned mass murderer - fled to Moscow on a Russian military plane, reportedly with only the clothes on his back. The red-black-white-green flag of the revolution flies again over government buildings. For millions of Syrians this is the moment of pure, disbelieving joy. Yet joy is a fragile guest in a country that has endured thirteen years of industrial-scale slaughter, displacement and despair. The fall of Damascus does not mark the end of Syria's war; it merely opens the most perilous chapter yet. The regime has collapsed with astonishing speed, but the state it hollowed out has collapsed with it. There is no functioning army, no police, no civil service, no electricity grid worthy of the name. Prisons that held tens of thousands of the disappeared are being thrown open by relatives wielding angle-grinders and hope. In some neighbourhoods former detainees are already exacting summary revenge on captured regime officials. The rule of law is a phrase from another lifetime. The coalition that finally toppled Assad is itself a marriage of convenience rather than conviction. Hayat Tahrir al-Sham (HTS), the jihadist-dominated group that led the lightning offensive from Idlib, has spent years on western terrorist lists. Its leader, Abu Mohammed al-Jolani, may have swapped combat fatigues for suits and spoken eloquently about inclusive governance in recent interviews, but his organisation's al-Qaida roots and its brutal rule in Idlib are not ancient history. Turkish-backed factions in the north bring their own sectarian baggage and competing agendas. Kurdish forces in the east, having sat out the final assault, will not accept domination by Arab Islamists. And in the south Druze militias are already arming against any attempt to impose uniform rule from Damascus. Russia and Iran - the regime's longtime patrons - have been humiliated. Moscow's airbase at Hmeimim remains, but its ability to project power has evaporated overnight. Tehran has lost its most precious Arab ally and the land bridge to Hezbollah. Both will scheme to retain influence, possibly by backing Alawite separatists along the coast or stirring proxy chaos. Israel, meanwhile, has wasted no time: its jets have struck dozens of Syrian military sites since Sunday, determined to prevent advanced weapons falling into unfriendly hands. The Golan Heights buffer zone has been unilaterally expanded. No one in Syria is under any illusion about who holds real power in the skies. The humanitarian emergency is apocalyptic. Fourteen million people - two-thirds of the remaining population - need aid. Winter has arrived with temperatures dropping below zero in the mountains. Fuel shortages mean that even where bakeries stand there is nothing to bake.`
