    title: "Typing Mitra DSSSB 93",
    difficulty: "Hard",
    text: `Donald Trump took office last month promising the "largest domestic deportation operation in American history", and he has wasted no time. Within days executive orders were signed, ICE budgets tripled, and military aircraft requisitioned to fly shackled migrants to El Salvador, Honduras and Haiti. Television screens now show nightly images of crying children pulled from classrooms, parents dragged from hospital beds, and long-term residents - many with American-born children - loaded onto buses in dawn raids. The target is 11 million people, perhaps 13 million. The method is terror. The cost, in every sense, will be astronomical. This is not immigration enforcement; it is ethnic cleansing by another name. The plan relies on ending birthright citizenship (despite the plain text of the 14th amendment), cancelling protected status for half a million Venezuelans and Haitians, and invoking the 1798 Alien Enemies Act to bypass due process entirely. Local police are being pressed into service through 287(g) agreements, turning every traffic stop into a potential deportation trigger. Universities have been warned that foreign students attending pro-Palestine rallies risk revocation of visas. Even legal permanent residents with decades-old minor convictions are being rounded up. Fear has become the governing principle. The human toll is already measurable. Suicide hotlines report record calls from Spanish-speaking callers. School absenteeism in Latino neighbourhoods has spiked 40 %. Hospitals note a sharp drop in undocumented patients seeking care for chronic conditions. Farmers in California and Texas warn of crops rotting in fields; construction sites in Florida stand half-empty. The American Immigration Council estimates that removing 11 million people would shrink US GDP by 4.2-6.8 % - a self-inflicted wound larger than the financial crash. Texas alone would lose $400bn in economic output over a decade. These are not abstract numbers; they are wages not paid, taxes not collected, businesses shuttered. Yet the cruelty is the point. Stephen Miller, the architect of family separation in 2018, is back in the White House with greater power. The administration speaks openly of "deterrence through severity" and "making America unlivable for illegals". Camps are being prepared on military bases; private prison corporations have seen their share prices double since November. When journalists ask about the fate of mixed-status families, officials shrug and repeat the slogan "they should have thought of that before coming". Empathy has been declared a national-security liability. Democrats, still reeling from their electoral defeat, have offered only muted criticism. Some red-state governors quietly beg for exemptions for dairy workers and roofers. The courts will eventually be asked to intervene, but Trump has packed the judiciary with loyalists and openly threatens defiance of "so-called judges". Congress, paralysed by Republican control of both chambers, shows no appetite for legislative fixes. A nation founded by immigrants and built by their labour is choosing to tear itself apart rather than confront the reality that its economy and society are inseparable from the very people it now demonises.`
