    id: 94,
    title: "Typing Mitra DSSSB 94",
    difficulty: "Hard",
    text: `This summer the Arctic Ocean turned the deepest shade of blue scientists have ever recorded. Satellite images show open water where thick multiyear ice once stood impervious to the sun. The North-West Passage opened in June - the earliest on record - and stayed navigable into November. Cargo ships now steam from Yokohama to Rotterdam in half the time it took a decade ago, shaving thousands of kilometres off old routes. Tourists on luxury icebreakers sip champagne while photographing polar bears stranded on shrinking floes. Governments and corporations speak excitedly of "new shipping lanes" and "untapped resources". They rarely mention that the Arctic sea ice has declined 13 % per decade since 1979, or that the region is warming four times faster than the global average. A "blue ocean event" - an ice-free summer Arctic - once dismissed as a late-century possibility is now projected by some models within the next five to ten years. The consequences reach far beyond the polar circle. Arctic amplification drives extreme weather across the northern hemisphere. When the temperature difference between equator and pole narrows, the jet stream weakens and meanders, locking heatwaves over Europe and floods over Pakistan for weeks at a time. The 2021 Pacific north-west heat dome that killed hundreds, the 2022 European drought that emptied rivers, the 2025 monsoon deluge that drowned Lahore - all carry the Arctic's fingerprint. Permafrost containing twice as much carbon as currently exists in the atmosphere is already thawing, releasing methane in quantities that dwarf human emissions. Greenland's ice sheet shed a record 600 billion tonnes last year alone, contributing to sea-level rise that now threatens coastal cities from Miami to Mumbai. Yet the response remains grotesquely inadequate. The eight Arctic Council nations continue to licence new oil and gas drilling even as they pledge net zero by 2050. Norway boasts of being "carbon neutral" while exporting record volumes of fossil fuels. Russia plans to double shipping through the Northern Sea Route by 2035, powered by diesel tankers that blacken remaining ice with soot and accelerate melting. Canada quietly approves deep-sea mining exploration on its Arctic shelf. China styles itself a "near-Arctic state" and builds ice-capable LNG carriers to exploit the very catastrophe it helps create. All of them hide behind the fiction that Arctic resources can be extracted "responsibly". Indigenous communities pay the first and heaviest price. In Nunavut suicide rates among young Inuit have tripled as traditional hunting routes vanish. S?mi reindeer herders watch lichen buried under rain instead of snow. Entire villages in Alaska are being relocated as coastlines crumble. Their knowledge - accumulated over millennia - is ignored when it conflicts with profit.`
