    id: 95,
    title: "Typing Mitra DSSSB 95",
    difficulty: "Medium",
    text: `France is burning again - not with the fury of the gilets jaunes this time, but with a colder, more determined anger. Since September the streets of Paris, Marseille and Lyon have filled with millions marching against Emmanuel Macron's decision to raise the retirement age from 62 to 64. Trade unions, usually fractured, have united in the longest general strike since 1968. Trains stand idle, refineries are blockaded, rubbish piles high in the capital, and schools remain shut week after week. The president responds with lectures about "responsibility" and "modernisation", seemingly oblivious to the fact that two-thirds of voters oppose his reform. His approval rating has collapsed below 30 %. The Fifth Republic itself feels suddenly fragile. Macron's mistake was not the reform itself - France's pension system does face long-term funding pressure - but the contempt with which he forced it through. After losing his parliamentary majority last year he invoked article 49.3 of the constitution to bypass a vote not once but nineteen times in six months. When deputies moved to censure the government he survived by just nine votes. The message was unmistakable: the French people may speak, but only the president decides. The numbers tell a different story from the one Macron repeats. French workers already retire later than Germans when years spent in disability or unemployment are counted. They contribute more and receive less than their pensions average ?1 400 a month after a lifetime of work compared with 2100 in Italy and 2500 in Spain. Women, who dominate part-time and low-paid sectors, will be hit hardest by longer contribution requirements. Manual workers - builders, cleaners, care assistants - rarely reach 64 with bodies intact. Life expectancy in the poorest districts of Marseille is twelve years lower than in the wealthy 7th arrondissement of Paris. Macron's reform is not technocratic adjustment; it is social violence dressed as arithmetic. Behind the rage lies a deeper betrayal. Macron swept to power promising to transcend left and right, to protect workers while modernising the economy. Instead he has governed as the president of the rich - cutting wealth tax, shielding corporate profits, praising "first in the morning, last at night" entrepreneurs while dismissing struggling citizens as "people who are nothing". The pensions decree is merely the final straw in a presidency that has grown increasingly remote and monarchical.`
