    title: "Typing Mitra DSSSB 96",
    difficulty: "Medium",
    text: `Another week, another hospital in Gaza reduced to rubble. Last Thursday Israeli missiles struck the Indonesian Hospital in Beit Lahiya just hours after the army ordered evacuation. Patients on dialysis were carried out on stretchers, premature babies removed from incubators, surgeons operating by mobile-phone light fled mid-procedure. The World Health Organisation reports that only twelve of Gaza's thirty-six hospitals remain even partially functional. More than healthcare workers have been killed since October 2023. Medical supplies are blocked at the border while children die of treatable infections. The pattern is now so routine that it barely makes headlines, yet each attack is a separate war crime under international humanitarian law. Israel insists it targets only Hamas fighters hiding in medical facilities. Sometimes it presents grainy drone footage of alleged tunnels or weapons caches. Even if these claims were universally true - and many have been debunked by independent investigators - they would not justify the systematic destruction of an entire healthcare system. The laws of war are explicit: hospitals lose protected status only if used to commit "acts harmful to the enemy" and only after due warning and time to evacuate. In practice warnings are often issued minutes before strikes, evacuation routes are bombed, and neighbouring facilities are hit days later. The result is collective punishment of the most vulnerable - cancer patients, pregnant women, newborns in intensive care. The statistics are numbing in their horror. Gaza's health ministry - deemed reliable by UN agencies - reports more than 45 000 dead, a third of them children. Malnutrition rates among under-fives exceed famine thresholds. Polio has returned after twenty-five years, spreading through sewage-contaminated water because desalination plants lack fuel. Maternal mortality has tripled. Surgeons operate without anaesthesia; amputations on children have become daily routine. The Israeli medical association has remained almost entirely silent while its Palestinian counterparts are killed at work. This is not collateral damage; it is policy. Military spokesmen speak openly of making Gaza "uninhabitable" to pressure Hamas. The defence minister has called Palestinians "human animals" and imposed total siege. When doctors appeal for safe corridors they are accused of terrorist sympathies. When journalists document the carnage they are denied entry or targeted - 180 killed so far, the deadliest conflict ever for media workers.`
