    text: `South Korea has recorded the world's lowest fertility rate for the fifth year running - 0.72 children per woman. Japan, Italy and Spain hover below 1.3. Even India, long assumed immune, has fallen to 1.9. Britain, France and the United States are all at or below replacement level. The global population bomb has been replaced by a demographic time bomb, and almost no society is ready. The causes are no mystery. Women have gained education and workplace rights but childcare remains expensive, housing unaffordable, and careers still punish motherhood. Men have not taken up equal domestic labour. Workplaces demand ever-longer hours while wages stagnate. Climate anxiety, political instability and the cost-of-living crisis have convinced an entire generation that bringing children into the world is irresponsible. In Seoul young people speak openly of "sampo" - giving up dating, marriage and children because life is too precarious. Politicians reach for old levers: baby bonuses, tax breaks, extended parental leave. Hungary offers lifetime income-tax exemption for mothers of four or more. Poland pays ?800 per child per month. Results are meagre. Money helps at the margins but cannot buy time, housing or optimism. The consequences are already here. Schools close for lack of pupils. Universities shrink. Pension systems wobble as fewer workers support more retirees. Japan has more adult diapers sold than baby nappies. Care homes in rural Italy stand empty for lack of staff. Immigration is the obvious solution, yet anti-migrant politics makes it toxic almost everywhere. Some celebrate falling population as ecological salvation. Fewer humans mean less pressure on the planet. But the transition will be brutal without planning. Economies built on endless growth will contract. Innovation may slow as workforces age. Power will shift from young, populous nations to old, rich ones - unless the rich ones open their borders. There are better paths. Universal childcare, genuinely shared parental leave, flexible working as default, and housing policies that favour families over landlords. Societies must decide whether children are a private luxury goods or public goods essential to the common future. Until that question is answered honestly, fertility will keep falling - and the world will keep ageing, one empty playground at a time.`
