    difficulty: "Hard",
    text: `Across Europe families are choosing between heating and eating while governments scramble to fill gas-storage sites before the first hard frost. Prices have tripled since 2021, industry has curtailed production, and the continent that once lectured the world on climate leadership is burning more coal than at any point this century. Russia supplies only 8 % of EU gas now - down from 40 % - yet Vladimir Putin has lost none of his leverage. A single twist of the tap in Siberia or a drone strike on Ukrainian pipelines is enough to send wholesale prices soaring again. The age of cheap Russian energy is over, but Europe has not yet escaped its dependence. The scramble to replace Moscow's molecules has produced a moral and strategic mess. Tankers carrying American LNG dock daily, yet the gas is extracted by fracking and arrives with a carbon footprint larger than pipeline gas. Norway has become Europe's reluctant swing supplier, pumping fields at maximum capacity while its own climate targets slip. Qatar and Algeria demand decades-long contracts at take-or-pay prices. Egypt and Israel sell gas that was meant for their own citizens. Meanwhile Britain, having left the single market, begs for emergency electricity imports from France and pays whatever the French grid operator demands. Households have borne the brunt. Energy bills in Germany have risen 70 %, in Italy 120 %, in Britain 180 %. Pensioners turn off fridges to save money. Food banks report people returning tins because they cannot afford the electricity to heat them. Small businesses close early to avoid peak tariffs. The European Central Bank now lists energy poverty as a systemic risk to financial stability. Governments have spent 700bn on subsidies and price caps - more than the entire Marshall Plan in today's money - yet the relief is temporary and regressive. The richest tenth of households receive almost as much subsidy as the poorest tenth because everyone pays the same capped unit price. A German billionaire's heated swimming pool is subsidised at the same rate as a Romanian grandmother's single radiator. The long-term answers exist but require political courage politicians refuse to show. A windfall tax on energy giants that properly claws back unearned profits. Massive public investment in insulation - Britain alone has 19 million draughty homes. A single European energy market that pools storage and purchasing power instead of letting member states bid against each other. And above all an accelerated transition to renewables that ends fossil-fuel imports for good. Until then Putin can sit back and watch Europe tear up its climate ambitions every winter. He no longer needs to invade countries; he simply waits for the temperature to drop. The whip hand remains his.`
