    text: `Traffic problems in Indian cities have become a major general issue that affects millions of people every single day and wastes a lot of productive time. In metropolitan cities like Delhi Mumbai Kolkata and Chennai the roads are so crowded with cars buses scooters and auto-rickshaws that moving even a short distance takes hours during peak hours. Many drivers do not follow traffic rules and jump red lights or overtake from the wrong side which increases the risk of accidents and creates chaos on the roads. Pedestrians have a hard time crossing busy streets because there are very few zebra crossings and foot over-bridges. Two-wheelers are very popular because they are cheap and easy to maneuver in traffic but they also cause many accidents due to rash driving and lack of helmets. Public transport systems like buses and metro trains are overloaded especially during morning and evening rush hours forcing people to hang from doors or travel in extremely cramped conditions. The number of vehicles is increasing rapidly every year while the road infrastructure is not expanding at the same pace leading to frequent traffic jams and pollution. Air quality becomes very poor in cities because of smoke from vehicles which causes respiratory problems like asthma and bronchitis among children and elderly people. Parking is another big headache as there are not enough parking spaces and vehicles are often parked on roadsides blocking the smooth flow of traffic. The government has tried to solve this by building flyovers metro rails and wider roads but construction work itself causes more congestion and diverts traffic to narrow lanes. Corruption in traffic police departments sometimes leads to selective enforcement of rules where only poor drivers are fined while influential people escape easily. Many accidents happen because of potholes on roads that damage vehicles and cause drivers to lose control suddenly. During monsoon season the situation becomes worse because water logging on roads makes driving dangerous and increases the chances of skidding. Women and senior citizens feel unsafe while traveling alone at night due to poor street lighting and increasing cases of harassment in public transport. Cycle tracks and pedestrian paths are almost non-existent in most cities making it difficult for people who want to use environment-friendly modes of travel. The introduction of ride-sharing apps like Uber and Ola has provided some relief but surge pricing during peak hours makes it expensive for daily commuters.`
