    text: `Poverty remains one of the most challenging general issues in India despite the economic growth seen in recent decades because a significant portion of the population still lives below the poverty line. In rural areas many families depend on daily wage labor in agriculture or construction and their income is irregular and insufficient to meet basic needs like food clothing and shelter. Children from poor families often drop out of school to support their parents by working in fields or small shops which perpetuates the cycle of poverty across generations. Urban slums are crowded with migrants who come in search of jobs but end up living in unhygienic conditions without proper electricity water or sanitation facilities. Malnutrition and hunger are common among poor households especially affecting pregnant women and young children who suffer from stunted growth and weak immunity. Government schemes like Public Distribution System provide subsidized food grains but leakages and corruption sometimes prevent the benefits from reaching the intended beneficiaries. Women in poor families face double disadvantage because they have limited access to education healthcare and income-generating opportunities due to traditional gender roles. Old age pension and disability allowances exist but the amounts are small and the process of getting them is complicated with long delays. Debt traps are common as poor people borrow from local moneylenders at exorbitant interest rates when they face emergencies like illness or crop failure. Seasonal migration is frequent as families move to cities during lean agricultural periods leaving children behind or taking them out of school. Microfinance and self-help groups have helped many women start small businesses but scaling up remains difficult due to lack of markets and skills. The digital divide is widening because poor households cannot afford smartphones or internet which limits their access to government services online education and job opportunities. Climate change and natural disasters like floods droughts and cyclones hit poor communities the hardest because they have no savings or insurance to recover quickly. Social discrimination based on caste and religion sometimes restricts access to jobs and resources for certain groups living in poverty. The government has launched programs like MGNREGA to provide guaranteed wage employment in rural areas and Pradhan Mantri Awas Yojana for housing but implementation quality varies across states. Skill development for youth from poor backgrounds can help them get better-paying jobs if training is linked with industry requirements.`
