    text: `Climate change extreme weather events and environmental concerns are becoming more serious issues for India because rising temperatures unpredictable rainfall and increasing pollution are affecting agriculture water resources and public health across different regions. Farmers in many states are struggling with erratic monsoon patterns droughts or sudden floods that damage crops and reduce income while cities face severe air pollution and water scarcity that impact daily life and increase healthcare costs. Balancing rapid economic development with the need to protect forests rivers and biodiversity is a big challenge because many infrastructure and industrial projects face opposition from environmental groups and local communities. The government is promoting renewable energy electric vehicles and green technologies but the transition is slow and the country still depends heavily on coal and fossil fuels for its energy needs. Coastal areas are worried about rising sea levels and stronger cyclones while Himalayan regions are seeing faster melting of glaciers that can cause floods and affect water supply for millions. Public awareness is growing but changing habits and enforcing stricter pollution control measures require continuous effort from both government and citizens. International commitments like reducing carbon emissions are important but India also has to ensure that its development needs are not compromised. As April twenty twenty six begins the impact of climate change is visible in many parts of the country and experts are calling for better disaster preparedness stronger forest conservation and sustainable farming practices. Young people and students are taking active interest in environmental issues and demanding faster action from leaders. The coming years will test how successfully India can grow its economy while keeping the environment healthy for future generations.`
