    text: `As India hosts the global summit on Artificial Intelligence in New Delhi, the focus has shifted decisively toward building a robust domestic ecosystem for Agentic AI and large language models tailored for Indian languages. The government's new draft procurement policy, which prioritizes local technology, marks a significant increase in budgetary support for indigenous chip design and high-end manufacturing. With several major Indian companies expected to begin commercial semiconductor production at the Dholera plant by mid-2026, the goal of Atmanirbhar Bharat in the high-tech sector looks increasingly like a tangible reality rather than a distant dream. However, this journey toward tech sovereignty must be complemented by strong cybersecurity frameworks to protect against AI-driven threats that are becoming more sophisticated and frequent. The projected growth of the Indian AI market offers a massive opportunity for startups, but it also necessitates a regulatory environment that encourages innovation while protecting data privacy. The Digital Personal Data Protection Act of 2023 provides the foundation, but its implementation through rules and a dedicated Data Protection Board is still in the nascent stages. Furthermore, the shift toward AI in the services sector could impact a portion of the entry-level workforce, making re-skilling and vocational training a national priority. India's advantage lies in its vast data sets and its engineering talent, but converting these into global leadership requires a sustained partnership between the state, the private sector, and academia. The AI for All mission must ensure that the benefits of this fourth industrial revolution reach the last mile, empowering farmers with predictive analytics and students with personalized learning tools in their mother tongues. We must also address the ethical dimensions of AI, particularly in the context of deepfakes which have increased significantly in the lead-up to the current election cycle. An expert committee is currently drafting the AI Ethics Guidelines, which will mandate a digital watermark for all AI-generated content. Without such safeguards, the increase in broadband penetration could inadvertently become a tool for mass misinformation. The government has allocated a large sum for the India AI Mission, which includes the installation of a supercomputing infrastructure to be made available to Indian researchers at a subsidized rate.`
