    title: "Typing Mitra DSSSB 239",
    difficulty: "Medium",
    text: `The fatal stampede at the Sheetla Mata Temple in Bihar's Nalanda district is a grim reminder of the persistent and heartbreaking gaps in crowd management at large religious gatherings in India. Many lives were lost, mostly women and elderly citizens, when a massive crowd of devotees exceeded the temple's documented capacity on the last Monday of the Chaitra month. Reports suggest that security was significantly compromised as local police personnel were diverted for a high-profile visit of the President to a nearby university, highlighting a systemic failure to prioritize public safety over VIP movements. It is high time that the authorities adopt scientific crowd-control protocols, including real-time digital monitoring and drone surveillance, to prevent such avoidable disasters from recurring in our spiritual hubs. The Bihar government's announcement of an ex gratia payment to the families of the deceased is a necessary gesture of support, but it cannot replace the need for accountability and structural reform in temple administration. Previous commissions of inquiry into similar incidents at Sabarimala and Allahabad have recommended strict caps on entry and the creation of wide exit corridors, yet these guidelines remain largely on paper in the smaller districts. The suspension of the Station House Officer is a start, but the Special Investigation Team must look into why the standard operating procedures for large-scale festivals were not triggered despite the known influx of pilgrims. As our population grows and religious tourism expands, the mela culture of India must evolve into a modern, managed experience where faith does not come at the cost of life. Public safety should be a non-negotiable component of the district administration's annual calendar, supported by a dedicated budget for event-based policing and emergency medical response. Furthermore, the lack of medical facilities within a small radius of the shrine meant that the many injured individuals faced critical delays in receiving basic trauma care. This delay in medical intervention often marks the difference between life and death in crush-related injuries. The local administration's claim that they were unaware of the scale of the gathering is a weak defense, given that mobile network data showed a massive surge in user density in the area hours before the tragedy occurred. A failure to utilize such real-time technological indicators represents a dereliction of duty that warrants a high-level judicial probe into the nexus of administrative apathy and the lack of basic infrastructure.`
